# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pitch-shifting
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune was initially intended to disguise or correct off-key inaccuracies, allowing vocal tracks to be perfectly tuned.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Cher's 1998 song "Believe" popularized the use of AutoTune to deliberately distort vocals, a technique that became known as the "Cher effect".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] It has since been used by many artists in different genres, including Daft Punk, Radiohead, T-Pain and Kanye West.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] In 2018, the music critic Simon Reynolds felt that AutoTune had "revolutionized popular music", calling its use for effects "the fad that just wouldn't fade.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune is available as a plug-in for digital audio workstations used in a studio setting and as a stand-alone, rack-mounted unit for live performance processing.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The processor slightly shifts pitches to the nearest true, correct semitone (to the exact pitch of the nearest note in traditional equal temperament).
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune can also be used as an effect to distort the human voice when pitch is raised or lowered significantly, such that the voice is heard to leap from note to note stepwise, like a synthesizer.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune has become standard equipment in professional recording studios.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Instruments such as the Peavey AT-200 guitar seamlessly use AutoTune technology for real-time pitch correction.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune was developed in 1997 by Andy Hildebrand, a Ph.D. research engineer who specialized in stochastic estimation theory and digital signal processing.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] He conceived it following the suggestion of a colleague's wife, who had joked that she would benefit from a device to help her sing in tune.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Over several months in early 1996, Hildebrand implemented the algorithm on a custom Macintosh computer.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Hildebrand's method for detecting pitch involved autocorrelation and proved superior to attempts based on feature extraction, which had problems processing elements such as diphthongs, leading to sound artifacts.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Music engineers had previously considered autocorrelation impractical because of the massive computational effort required.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Hildebrand found a mathematical method to overcome this, "a simplification [that] changed a million multiply adds into just four".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] On October 18, 2016, after nearly two decades of independent operation under Hildebrand, Antares Audio Technologies was acquired by Broadstream Capital Partners, a merchant bank based in Calabasas, California, in partnership with Corbel Capital Partners.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] On April 26, 2019, Corbel Capital Partners realized its investment when Antares was acquired by a prominent New York-based family office.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The Aphex Twin track "Funny Little Man", from the 1997 EP *Come to Daddy*, was released less than a month after AutoTune and was one of the earliest tracks to use it.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Cher's 1998 single "Believe" was the first commercial recording to use AutoTune as a stylistic effect, creating a robotic, futuristic sound.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Cher, who proposed the effect, faced resistance from her label but insisted it remain.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] While AutoTune was designed to be used subtly to correct vocal performances, the "Believe" producers used extreme settings to create unnaturally rapid corrections in Cher's vocals, thereby removing portamento, the natural slide between pitches in speech and singing.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Though AutoTune had been commercially available for about a year, according to *Pitchfork*, "Believe" was the first song "where the effect drew attention to itself ... announcing its technological artifice".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] In an attempt to protect their method, the producers initially claimed the effect was achieved with a vocoder.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] According to *Pitchfork*, 1999 "Too Much of Heaven" by the Italian Europop group Eiffel 65 features the first example of rapping through AutoTune.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The Eiffel 65 member Gabry Ponte said they were inspired by "Believe".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The rock band Radiohead used AutoTune on their 2001 album *Amnesiac* to create a "nasal, depersonalized sound" and to process speech into melody.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] According to the Radiohead singer, Thom Yorke, AutoTune "desperately tries to search for the music in your speech, and produces notes at random.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Later in the 2000s, T-Pain used AutoTune extensively, further popularizing the use of the effect.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] He cited the new jack swing producer Teddy Riley and funk artist Roger Troutman's use of the talk box as inspirations.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] T-Pain became so associated with AutoTune that he had an iPhone app named after him that simulated the effect, "I Am T-Pain".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Eventually dubbed the "T-Pain effect", the use of AutoTune became a fixture of late 2000s music, where it was used in other hip-hop/R&B artists' works, including Snoop Dogg's single "Sexual Eruption", Lil Wayne's "Lollipop", and Kanye West's album *808s & Heartbreak*.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] In 2009 the Black Eyed Peas' number-one hit "Boom Boom Pow", made heavy use of AutoTune on their vocals to create a futuristic sound.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune in hip-hop resurged in the mid-2010s, especially in trap music.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Future and Young Thug are considered to the pioneers of modern trap music and have mentored or inspired artists such as Lil Baby, Gunna, Playboi Carti, Travis Scott, and Lil Uzi Vert.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune is popular in raï music and other Northern Africa genres.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] According to the *Boston Herald*, the country singers Faith Hill, Shania Twain, and Tim McGraw use AutoTune in performance, calling it a safety net that guarantees a good performance.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] However, country singers such as Allison Moorer, Garth Brooks, Big & Rich, Trisha Yearwood, Vince Gill and Martina McBride have refused to use AutoTune.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Some critics have argued that AutoTune opens up new possibilities in pop music, especially in hip-hop and R&B.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Instead of using it as a correction tool for poor vocals—its original purpose—some musicians intentionally use the technology to mediate and augment their artistic expression.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] When the electronic duo Daft Punk was asked about their use of AutoTune in their single "One More Time", Thomas Bangalter replied, "A lot of people complain about musicians using AutoTune.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] It reminds me of the late '70s when musicians in France tried to ban the synthesizer...
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] T-Pain, the R&B singer and rapper who reintroduced the use of AutoTune as a vocal effect in pop music with his album *Rappa Ternt Sanga* in 2005, said, "My dad always told me that anyone's voice is just another instrument added to the music.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] There was a time when people had seven-minute songs, and five minutes were just straight instrumental. ...
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] I got a lot of influence from [the '60s era].
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] I thought I might as well turn my voice into a saxophone." Following in T-Pain's footsteps, Lil Wayne experimented with AutoTune between his albums *Tha Carter II* and *Tha Carter III*.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] At the time, he was heavily addicted to promethazine codeine, and some critics see AutoTune as a musical expression of Wayne's loneliness and depression.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Mark Anthony Neal wrote that Lil Wayne's vocal uniqueness, his "slurs, blurs, bleeps and blushes of his vocals, index some variety of trauma." And Kevin Driscoll asks, "Is AutoTune not the wah pedal of today's black pop?
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Before he transformed himself into T-Wayne on "Lollipop", Wayne's pop presence was limited to guest verses and unauthorized freestyles.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Kanye West's *808s & Heartbreak* was generally well received by critics, and it similarly used AutoTune to represent a fragmented soul following his mother's death.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The album marks a departure from his previous album, *Graduation*.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Describing the album as a breakup album, *Rolling Stone* music critic Jody Rosen wrote, "Kanye can't really sing in the classic sense, but he's not trying to.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] T-Pain taught the world that AutoTune doesn't just sharpen flat notes: It's a painterly device for enhancing vocal expressiveness and upping the pathos ...
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] YouTuber Conor Maynard, who was criticised for his use of AutoTune, defended it in an interview on the *Zach Sang Show* in 2019, stating: "It doesn't mean you can't sing ...
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune can't make anyone who can't sing sound like they can sing ...
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] At the 51st Grammy Awards in 2009, the band Death Cab for Cutie made an appearance wearing blue ribbons to protest the use of AutoTune.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Later that year, Jay-Z released the single "D.O.A.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Jay-Z said he felt Auto-Tune had become a gimmick that was too widely used.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Christina Aguilera appeared in public in Los Angeles on August 10, 2009, wearing a T-shirt that read "Auto Tune is for pussies".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] When interviewed by Sirius/XM, she said AutoTune could be used "in a creative way" and noted her song "Elastic Love" from *Bionic* uses it.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Opponents have argued that AutoTune has a negative effect on the perception and consumption of music.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] In 2004, the *Daily Telegraph* critic Neil McCormick called AutoTune a "particularly sinister invention".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] In 2006, the singer-songwriter Neko Case said a studio employee once told her that she and Nelly Furtado were the only singers who had never used it in his studio.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Case said "it's cool that she has some integrity".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] In 2009, *Time* quoted an unidentified Grammy-winning recording engineer: "Let's just say I've had AutoTune save vocals on everything from Britney Spears to Bollywood cast albums.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] And every singer now presumes that you'll just run their voice through the box." The same article expressed "hope that pop's fetish for uniform perfect pitch will fade", speculating that pop songs had become harder to differentiate, as "track after track has perfect pitch".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] According to Tom Lord-Alge in 2009, AutoTune was used on nearly every modern record.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] In 2009, the producer Rick Rubin wrote that "Right now, if you listen to pop, everything is in perfect pitch, perfect time and perfect tune.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] That's how ubiquitous AutoTune is." In 2010, the reality TV show *The X Factor* admitted to using AutoTune to improve the voices of contestants.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] *Time* included AutoTune in its list of "the 50 worst inventions", and the *Time* journalist Josh Tyrangiel called Auto-Tune "Photoshop for the human voice".
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] AutoTune has been criticized as indicative of an inability to sing on key.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Trey Parker used it on the *South Park* song "Gay Fish", and found that he had to sing off-key to sound distorted.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] He said, "You had to be a bad singer in order for that thing to actually sound the way it does.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] If you use it and sing into it correctly, it doesn't do anything to your voice." The singer Kesha has used AutoTune extensively, putting her vocal talent under scrutiny.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The big band singer Michael Bublé criticized AutoTune as making everyone sound the same – "like robots" – but said he used it when recording pop music.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Ellie Goulding and Ed Sheeran joined the "Live Means Live" campaign, launched by the songwriter David Mindel in 2014.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Participating acts display a "Live Means Live" logo, guaranteeing to the audience that they are not using AutoTune or backing tracks.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] In 2023, multiple creators on the social media platform TikTok were accused of using AutoTune in post-production to correct the pitch of singing videos presented to appear as live, casual performances.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Asked if AutoTune was "evil", Hildebrand responded: "Well, my wife wears makeup.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The US TV comedy series *Saturday Night Live* parodied AutoTune using the fictional white rapper Blizzard Man, who sang in a sketch: "Robot voice, robot voice!
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Satirist "Weird Al" Yankovic poked fun at the overuse of AutoTune, while commenting that it seemed here to stay, in a YouTube video commented on by various publications such as *Wired*.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] Starting in 2009, the use of AutoTune to create melodies from the audio in video newscasts was popularized by Brooklyn musician Michael Gregory, and later by the band the Gregory Brothers in their series *Songify the News*.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The Gregory Brothers digitally manipulated the recorded voices of politicians, news anchors, and political pundits to conform to a melody, making the figures appear to sing.
[src:pitch-shifting/autotune] The group achieved mainstream success with their "Bed Intruder Song" video, which became the most-watched YouTube video of 2010.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] In speech science and phonetics, a **formant** is the broad spectral maximum that results from an acoustic resonance of the human vocal tract.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] In acoustics, a formant is usually defined as a broad peak, or local maximum, in the spectrum.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] For harmonic sounds, with this definition, the formant frequency is sometimes taken as that of the harmonic that is most augmented by a resonance.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The difference between these two definitions resides in whether "formants" characterise the production mechanisms of a sound or the produced sound itself.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] In practice, the frequency of a spectral peak differs slightly from the associated resonance frequency, except when, by luck, harmonics are aligned with the resonance frequency, or when the sound source is mostly non-harmonic, as in whispering and vocal fry.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] A room can be said to have formants characteristic of that particular room, due to its resonances, i.e., to the way sound reflects from its walls and objects.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Room formants of this nature reinforce themselves by emphasizing specific frequencies and absorbing others, as exploited, for example, by Alvin Lucier in his piece *I Am Sitting in a Room*.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] In acoustic digital signal processing, the way a collection of formants (such as a room) affects a signal can be represented by an impulse response.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] In both speech and rooms, formants are characteristic features of the resonances of the space.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] They are said to be *excited* by acoustic sources such as the voice, and they shape (filter) the sources' sounds, but they are not sources themselves.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] From an acoustic point of view, phonetics had a serious problem with the idea that the effective length of vocal tract changed vowels.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Indeed, when the length of the vocal tract changes, all the acoustic resonators formed by mouth cavities are scaled, and so are their resonance frequencies.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Therefore, it was unclear how vowels could depend on frequencies when talkers with different vocal tract lengths, for instance bass and soprano singers, can produce sounds that are perceived as belonging to the same phonetic category.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] There had to be some way to normalize the spectral information underpinning the vowel identity.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Hermann suggested a solution to this problem in 1894, coining the term “formant”.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] A vowel, according to him, is a special acoustic phenomenon, depending on the intermittent production of a special partial, or “formant”, or “characteristique” feature.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The frequency of the “formant” may vary a little without altering the character of the vowel.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] For “long e” (*ee* or *iy*) for example, the lowest-frequency “formant” may vary from 350 to 440 Hz even in the same person.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Formants are distinctive frequency components of the acoustic signal produced by speech, musical instruments or singing.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The information that humans require to distinguish between speech sounds can be represented purely quantitatively by specifying peaks in the frequency spectrum.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Most of these formants are produced by tube and chamber resonance, but a few whistle tones derive from periodic collapse of Venturi effect low-pressure zones.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The formant with the lowest frequency is called *F*1, the second *F*2, the third *F*3, and so forth.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The fundamental frequency or pitch of the voice is sometimes referred to as *F*0, but it is not a formant.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Most often the two first formants, *F*1 and *F*2, are sufficient to identify the vowel.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The relationship between the perceived vowel quality and the first two formant frequencies can be appreciated by listening to "artificial vowels" that are generated by passing a click train (to simulate the glottal pulse train) through a pair of bandpass filters (to simulate vocal tract resonances).
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Front vowels have higher *F*2, while low vowels have higher *F*1.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Lip rounding tends to lower *F*1 and *F*2 in back vowels and *F*2 and *F*3 in front vowels.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Lowering of *F*3 is also a primary characteristic of r-colored vowels.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Nasal consonants usually have an additional formant around 2500 Hz.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The liquid [l] usually has an extra formant at 1500 Hz, whereas the English "r" sound ([ɹ]) is distinguished by a very low third formant (well below 2000 Hz).
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Plosives (and, to some degree, fricatives) modify the placement of formants in the surrounding vowels.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The time course of these changes in vowel formant frequencies are referred to as 'formant transitions'.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] In normal voiced speech, the underlying vibration produced by the vocal folds resembles a sawtooth wave, rich in harmonic overtones.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] If the fundamental frequency or (more often) one of the overtones is higher than a resonance frequency of the system, then the resonance will be only weakly excited and the formant usually imparted by that resonance will be mostly lost.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] This is most apparent in the case of soprano opera singers, who sing at pitches high enough that their vowels become very hard to distinguish.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Control of resonances is an essential component of the vocal technique known as overtone singing, in which the performer sings a low fundamental tone, and creates sharp resonances to select upper harmonics, giving the impression of several tones being sung at once.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Spectrograms may be used to visualise formants.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] In spectrograms, it can be hard to distinguish formants from naturally occurring harmonics when one sings.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] However, one can hear the natural formants in a vowel shape through atonal techniques such as vocal fry.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Formants, whether they are seen as acoustic resonances of the vocal tract, or as local maxima in the speech spectrum, like band-pass filters, are defined by their frequency and by their spectral width (bandwidth).
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Different methods exist to obtain this information.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Formant frequencies, in their acoustic definition, can be estimated from the frequency spectrum of the sound, using a spectrogram (in the figure) or a spectrum analyzer.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] However, to estimate the acoustic resonances of the vocal tract (i.e. the speech definition of formants) from a speech recording, one can use *linear predictive coding*.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] An intermediate approach consists in extracting the spectral envelope by neutralizing the fundamental frequency, and only then looking for local maxima in the spectral envelope.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The first two formants are important in determining the quality of vowels, and are frequently said to correspond to the open–close (or low–high) and front–back dimensions (which have traditionally been associated with the shape and position of the tongue).
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Thus the first formant *F*1 has a higher frequency for an open or low vowel such as [a] and a lower frequency for a closed or high vowel such as [i] or [u]; and the second formant *F*2 has a higher frequency for a front vowel such as [i] and a lower frequency for a back vowel such as [u].
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Vowels will almost always have four or more distinguishable formants, and sometimes more than six.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] However, the first two formants are the most important in determining vowel quality and are often plotted against each other in vowel diagrams, though this simplification fails to capture some aspects of vowel quality such as rounding.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Many writers have addressed the problem of finding an optimal alignment of the positions of vowels on formant plots with those on the conventional vowel quadrilateral.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] The pioneering work of Ladefoged used the Mel scale because this scale was claimed to correspond more closely to the auditory scale of pitch than to the acoustic measure of fundamental frequency expressed in Hertz.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Two alternatives to the Mel scale are the Bark scale and the ERB-rate scale.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Another widely adopted strategy is plotting the difference between *F*1 and *F*2 rather than *F*2 on the horizontal axis.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] Studies of the frequency spectrum of trained speakers and classical singers, especially male singers, indicate a clear formant around 3000 Hz (between 2800 and 3400 Hz) that is absent in speech or in the spectra of untrained speakers or singers.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] It is thought to be associated with one or more of the higher resonances of the vocal tract.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] It is this increase in energy at 3000 Hz which allows singers to be heard and understood over an orchestra.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] This formant is actively developed through vocal training, for instance through so-called *voce di strega* or "witch's voice" exercises and is caused by a part of the vocal tract acting as a resonator.
[src:pitch-shifting/formant] In classical music and vocal pedagogy, this phenomenon is also known as *squillo*.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] A **phase vocoder** is a type of vocoder-purposed algorithm which can interpolate information present in the frequency and time domains of audio signals by using phase information extracted from a frequency transform.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The computer algorithm allows frequency-domain modifications to a digital sound file (typically time expansion/compression and pitch shifting).
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] At the heart of the phase vocoder is the short-time Fourier transform (STFT), typically coded using fast Fourier transforms.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The time evolution of the resynthesized sound can be changed by means of modifying the time position of the STFT frames prior to the resynthesis operation allowing for time-scale modification of the original sound file.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The main problem that has to be solved for all cases of manipulation of the STFT is the fact that individual signal components (sinusoids, impulses) will be spread over multiple frames and multiple STFT frequency locations (bins).
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] This is because the STFT analysis is done using overlapping analysis windows.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The windowing results in spectral leakage such that the information of individual sinusoidal components is spread over adjacent STFT bins.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] To avoid border effects of tapering of the analysis windows, STFT analysis windows overlap in time.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] This time overlap results in the fact that adjacent STFT analyses are strongly correlated (a sinusoid present in analysis frame at time "t" will be present in the subsequent frames as well).
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The problem of signal transformation with the phase vocoder is related to the problem that all modifications that are done in the STFT representation need to preserve the appropriate correlation between adjacent frequency bins (vertical coherence) and time frames (horizontal coherence).
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The phase coherence problem was investigated for quite a while before appropriate solutions emerged.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The phase vocoder was introduced in 1966 by Flanagan as an algorithm that would preserve horizontal coherence between the phases of bins that represent sinusoidal components.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] This original phase vocoder did not take into account the vertical coherence between adjacent frequency bins, and therefore, time stretching with this system produced sound signals that were missing clarity.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The optimal reconstruction of the sound signal from STFT after amplitude modifications has been proposed by Griffin and Lim in 1984.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] This algorithm does not consider the problem of producing a coherent STFT, but it does allow finding the sound signal that has an STFT that is as close as possible to the modified STFT even if the modified STFT is not coherent (does not represent any signal).
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The problem of the vertical coherence remained a major issue for the quality of time scaling operations until 1999 when Laroche and Dolson proposed a means to preserve phase consistency across spectral bins.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The proposition of Laroche and Dolson has to be seen as a turning point in phase vocoder history.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] It has been shown that by means of ensuring vertical phase consistency very high quality time scaling transformations can be obtained.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The algorithm proposed by Laroche did not allow preservation of vertical phase coherence for sound onsets (note onsets).
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] A solution for this problem has been proposed by Roebel.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] An example of software implementation of phase vocoder based signal transformation using means similar to those described here to achieve high quality signal transformation is Ircam's SuperVP.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] British composer Trevor Wishart used phase vocoder analyses and transformations of a human voice as the basis for his composition *Vox 5* (part of his larger Vox Cycle).
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] *Transfigured Wind* by American composer Roger Reynolds uses the phase vocoder to perform time-stretching of flute sounds.
[src:pitch-shifting/phase-vocoder] The music of JoAnn Kuchera-Morin makes some of the earliest and most extensive use of phase vocoder transformations, such as in *Dreampaths* (1989).
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Pitch may be quantified as a frequency, but pitch is not a purely objective physical property; it is a subjective psychoacoustical attribute of sound.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Historically, the study of pitch and pitch perception has been a central problem in psychoacoustics, and has been instrumental in forming and testing theories of sound representation, processing, and perception in the auditory system.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Pitch is an auditory sensation in which a listener assigns musical tones to relative positions on a musical scale based primarily on their perception of the frequency of vibration (audio frequency).
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Pitch is closely related to frequency, but the two are not equivalent.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Frequency is an objective, scientific attribute which can be measured.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Pitch is the subjective perception of a sound wave by the individual person, which cannot be directly measured.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] However, this does not necessarily mean that people will not agree on which notes are higher and lower.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The oscillations of sound waves can often be characterized in terms of *frequency*.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] *Pitches* are usually associated with, and thus quantified as, *frequencies* (in cycles per second, or hertz), by comparing the sounds being assessed against sounds with pure tones (ones with periodic, sinusoidal waveforms).
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Complex and aperiodic sound waves can often be assigned a *pitch* by this method.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] According to the American National Standards Institute, pitch is the auditory attribute of sound allowing those sounds to be ordered on a scale from low to high.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Since pitch is such a close proxy for frequency, it is almost entirely determined by how quickly the sound wave is making the air vibrate and has almost nothing to do with the intensity, or amplitude, of the wave.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] That is, "high" pitch means very rapid oscillation, and "low" pitch corresponds to slower oscillation.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Despite that, the idiom relating vertical height to sound pitch is shared by most languages.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] At least in English, it is just one of many deep conceptual metaphors that involve up/down.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The exact etymological history of the musical sense of high and low pitch is still unclear.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] There is evidence that humans do actually perceive that the source of a sound is slightly higher or lower in vertical space when the sound frequency is increased or reduced.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In most cases, the pitch of complex sounds such as speech and musical notes corresponds very nearly to the repetition rate of periodic or nearly-periodic sounds, or to the reciprocal of the time interval between repeating similar events in the sound waveform.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The pitch of complex tones can be ambiguous, meaning that two or more different pitches can be perceived, depending upon the observer.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] When the actual fundamental frequency can be precisely determined through physical measurement, it may differ from the perceived pitch because of overtones, also known as upper partials, harmonic or otherwise.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] A complex tone composed of two sine waves of 1000 and 1200 Hz may sometimes be heard as up to three pitches: two spectral pitches at 1000 and 1200 Hz, derived from the physical frequencies of the pure tones, and the combination tone at 200 Hz, corresponding to the repetition rate of the waveform.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In a situation like this, the percept at 200 Hz is commonly referred to as the missing fundamental, which is often the greatest common divisor of the frequencies present.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Pitch depends to a lesser degree on the sound pressure level (loudness, volume) of the tone, especially at frequencies below 1,000 Hz and above 2,000 Hz.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The pitch of lower tones gets lower as sound pressure increases.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] For instance, a tone of 200 Hz that is very loud seems one semitone lower in pitch than if it is just barely audible.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Above 2,000 Hz, the pitch gets higher as the sound gets louder.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] These results were obtained in the pioneering works by S.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Cohen, have shown that in most cases the apparent pitch shifts were not significantly different from pitch‐matching errors.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] When averaged, the remaining shifts followed the directions of Stevens's curves but were small (2% or less by frequency, i.e. not more than a semitone).
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Theories of pitch perception try to explain how the physical sound and specific physiology of the auditory system work together to yield the experience of pitch.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In general, pitch perception theories can be divided into place coding and temporal coding.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Place theory holds that the perception of pitch is determined by the place of maximum excitation on the basilar membrane.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] A place code, taking advantage of the tonotopy in the auditory system, must be in effect for the perception of high frequencies, since neurons have an upper limit on how fast they can phase-lock their action potentials.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] However, a purely place-based theory cannot account for the accuracy of pitch perception in the low and middle frequency ranges.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Moreover, there is some evidence that some non-human primates lack auditory cortex responses to pitch despite having clear tonotopic maps in auditory cortex, showing that tonotopic place codes are not sufficient for pitch responses.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Temporal theories offer an alternative that appeals to the temporal structure of action potentials, mostly the phase-lock of action potentials to frequencies in a stimulus.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The precise way this temporal structure helps code for pitch at higher levels is still debated, but the processing seems to be based on an autocorrelation of action potentials in the auditory nerve.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] However, it has long been noted that a neural mechanism that may accomplish a delay—a necessary operation of a true autocorrelation—has not been found.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] To be a more complete model, autocorrelation must therefore apply to signals that represent the output of the cochlea, as via auditory-nerve interspike-interval histograms.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Some theories of pitch perception hold that pitch has inherent octave ambiguities, and therefore is best decomposed into a pitch *chroma*, a periodic value around the octave, like the note names in Western music—and a pitch *height*, which may be ambiguous, that indicates the octave the pitch is in.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The *just-noticeable difference* (JND), is the threshold at which a change in pitch is perceived.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] JND varies based on the tone's frequency content; below 500 Hz, the JND is about 3 Hz for sine waves, and 1 Hz for complex tones; above 1000 Hz, JND becomes about 0.6% for sine waves (about 10 cents).
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] This difference is typically tested by playing two tones in quick succession with the listener asked if there was a difference in their pitches, and becomes smaller if the two tones are played simultaneously as the listener is then able to discern beat frequencies.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The total number of perceptible pitch steps in the human hearing range is about 1,400; the total number of notes in the equal-tempered scale, from 16 to 16,000 Hz, is 120.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The relative perception of pitch can be fooled, resulting in *aural illusions*.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] There are several of these, such as the tritone paradox, but most notably the Shepard scale, where a continuous or discrete sequence of specially formed tones can be made to sound as if the sequence continues ascending or descending forever.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Not all musical instruments make notes with a clear pitch.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The unpitched percussion instruments (a class of percussion instruments) do not produce particular pitches.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] A sound or note of **definite pitch** is one where a listener can possibly (or relatively easily) discern the pitch.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Sounds with definite pitch have harmonic frequency spectra or close to harmonic spectra.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] A sound generated on any instrument produces many modes of vibration that occur simultaneously.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] A listener hears numerous frequencies at once.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The vibration with the lowest frequency is called the *fundamental frequency*; the other frequencies are *overtones*.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] *Harmonics* are an important class of overtones with frequencies that are integer multiples of the fundamental.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Whether or not the higher frequencies are integer multiples, they are collectively called the partials, referring to the different parts that make up the total spectrum.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] A sound or note of **indefinite pitch** is one that a listener finds impossible or relatively difficult to identify as to pitch.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Sounds with indefinite pitch do not have harmonic spectra or have altered harmonic spectra—a characteristic known as inharmonicity.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] It is still possible for two sounds of indefinite pitch to clearly be higher or lower than one another.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] For instance, a snare drum sounds higher pitched than a bass drum though both have indefinite pitch, because its sound contains higher frequencies.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In other words, it is possible and often easy to roughly discern the relative pitches of two sounds of indefinite pitch, but sounds of indefinite pitch do not neatly correspond to any specific pitch.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] A pitch standard is the conventional pitch reference that musical instruments in a group are tuned to for a performance.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] This may vary from ensemble to ensemble, and has varied widely over musical history.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Since 1939 the **A** above middle C is usually set at 440 Hz (often written as A440 or sometimes "A = 440 Hz"), although other frequencies, such as 442 Hz, are also often used as variants.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Another standard, the so-called 'baroque pitch', is now set at A = 415 Hz, a semitone lower than A440, so that period and modern instruments can be used together by transposing.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] 'Classical pitch' for fortepianos and other instruments for music of the Classical period can be tuned to either 427 Hz (about halfway between A415 and A440) or 430 Hz (also between A415 and A440 but slightly sharper than the quarter tone).
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] And ensembles specializing in authentic performance of repertoire from the Romantic era set the A above middle C to 432 Hz or the French standard until the 1930's of 435 Hz.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Transposing instruments conventionally have their parts transposed and written in different keys from voices and non-transposing instruments, and indeed from different transposing instruments.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] As a result, musicians speak of "concert pitch" to avoid ambiguity when talking to each other.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] For example, one might refer to the A above middle C as *a′*, *A4*, or *440 Hz*.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In standard Western equal temperament, the notion of pitch is insensitive to "spelling": the description "G4 double sharp" refers to the same pitch as *A4*; in other temperaments, these may be distinct pitches.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Human perception of musical intervals is approximately logarithmic with respect to fundamental frequency: the perceived interval between the pitches "A220" and "A440" is the same as the perceived interval between the pitches *A440* and *A880*.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Motivated by this logarithmic perception, music theorists sometimes represent pitches using a numerical scale based on the logarithm of fundamental frequency.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] For example, one can adopt the widely used MIDI standard to map fundamental frequency, *f*, to a real number, *p*, as follows.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] This creates a linear pitch space in which octaves have size 12, semitones (the distance between adjacent keys on the piano keyboard) have size 1, and A440 is assigned the number 69.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] (See Frequencies of notes.) Distance in this space corresponds to musical intervals as understood by musicians.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] An equal-tempered semitone is subdivided into 100 cents.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The system is flexible enough to include "microtones" not found on standard piano keyboards.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] For example, the pitch halfway between C (60) and C♯ (61) can be labeled 60.5.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] The relative pitches of individual notes in a scale may be determined by one of a number of tuning systems.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In the west, the twelve-note chromatic scale is the most common method of organization, with equal temperament now the most widely used method of tuning that scale.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In it, the pitch ratio between any two successive notes of the scale is exactly the twelfth root of two (or about 1.05946).
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In well-tempered systems (as used in the time of Johann Sebastian Bach, for example), different methods of musical tuning were used.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In almost all of these systems interval of the octave doubles the frequency of a note; for example, an octave above A440 is 880 Hz.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] If however the first overtone is sharp due to inharmonicity, as in the extremes of the piano, tuners resort to octave stretching.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In atonal, twelve tone, or musical set theory, a "pitch" is a specific frequency while a pitch class is all the octaves of a frequency.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] In many analytic discussions of atonal and post-tonal music, pitches are named with integers because of octave and enharmonic equivalency (for example, in a serial system, C♯ and D♭ are considered the same pitch, while C4 and C5 are functionally the same, one octave apart).
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Discrete pitches, rather than continuously variable pitches, are virtually universal, with exceptions including "tumbling strains" and "indeterminate-pitch chants".
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-music] Gliding pitches are used in most cultures, but are related to the discrete pitches they reference or embellish.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] The simplest methods are used to increase pitch and reduce durations or, conversely, reduce pitch and increase duration.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] This can be done by replaying a sound waveform at a different speed than it was recorded.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] It could be accomplished on an early reel-to-reel tape recorder by changing the diameter of the capstan or using a different motor.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] As for vinyl records, placing a finger on the turntable to give friction will slow it, while giving it a "spin" can advance it.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] As technologies improved, motor speed and pitch control could be achieved electronically by servo drive system circuits.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] A **pitch shifter** is a sound effects unit that raises or lowers the pitch of an audio signal by a preset interval.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] For example, a pitch shifter set to increase the pitch by a fourth will raise each note three diatonic intervals above the notes actually played.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Simple pitch shifters raise or lower the pitch by one or two octaves, while more sophisticated devices offer a range of interval alterations.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Pitch shifters are included in most audio processors today.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] A **harmonizer** is a type of pitch shifter that combines the pitch-shifted signal with the original to create a two or more note harmony.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] The Eventide H910 Harmonizer, released in 1975, was one of the first commercially available pitch-shifters and digital multi-effects units.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] On November 10, 1976, Eventide filed a trademark registration for "Harmonizer" and continues to maintain its rights to the Harmonizer trademark today.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] In digital recording, pitch shifting is accomplished through digital signal processing.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Older digital processors could often shift pitch only in post-production, whereas many modern devices using computer processing technology can change pitch values virtually in real time.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Pitch correction is a form of pitch shifting and is found in software such as Auto-Tune and Melodyne to correct intonation inaccuracies in a recording or performance.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Pitch shifting may raise or lower all sounds in a recording by the same amount, whereas in practice, pitch correction may make different changes from note to note.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Pitch shifting can be used in DJing for harmonic mixing, a technique of matching the musical key of tracks in a DJ mix to avoid dissonance and create harmonious mixes or mashups.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] If a DJ wishes to mix two tracks which are not in compatible keys, they can shift the pitch of one track so that its key is compatible with the other, allowing seamless transitions between tracks which might otherwise sound dissonant when played together.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Numerous cartoons have used pitch shifters to produce distinctive animal voices.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Alvin and the Chipmunks recordings with David Seville (aka Ross Bagdasarian) were created by recording vocal tracks at slow speeds, then playing them back at normal speeds.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Voice artist Mel Blanc used pitch shifting techniques to create the voices of Tweety and Daffy Duck.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] In the 1970s, reruns of shows like *I Love Lucy* were sped up in order to run more advertisements during commercial breaks.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] The Eventide H910 Harmonizer was used to downward pitch-shift the characters' voices back to normal after the episode was sped up.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] One notable early practitioner of pitch shifting in music is Chuck Berry, who used the technique to make his voice sound younger.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Many of the Beatles' records from 1966 and 1967 were made by recording instrumental tracks a half-step higher and the vocals correspondingly low.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Examples include "Rain", "I'm Only Sleeping", and "When I'm Sixty-Four".
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Electronic musician Burial is known for including pitch-shifted samples of vocal melodies in his songs.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] Goregrind and occasionally death metal use vocals that are often pitch-shifted to sound unnaturally low and guttural.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] The famous bass intro to the song "Seven Nation Army" by The White Stripes, is the result of guitarist Jack White playing an electric guitar through a pitch shifting effects pedal set to an octave below.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] The band was a duo, who lacked a bassist and had never previously used one in any of their music, choosing instead to mimic the sound of a bass guitar.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] From 1986 to 1988, American musician Prince used pitch shifting to create his “Camille” vocals.
[src:pitch-shifting/pitch-shift] The coda in the song “The Bewlay Brothers” by David Bowie features Bowie's voice distorted by varispeeding; this effect also appears throughout Bowie's 1967 song “The Laughing Gnome”.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The **short-time Fourier transform** (**STFT**) is a Fourier-related transform used to determine the sinusoidal frequency and phase content of local sections of a signal as it changes over time.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] In practice, the procedure for computing STFTs is to divide a longer time signal into shorter segments of equal length and then compute the Fourier transform separately on each shorter segment.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] This reveals the Fourier spectrum on each shorter segment.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] One then usually plots the changing spectra as a function of time, known as a spectrogram or waterfall plot, such as commonly used in software defined radio (SDR) based spectrum displays.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Full bandwidth displays covering the whole range of an SDR commonly use fast Fourier transforms (FFTs).
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Simply, in the continuous-time case, the function to be transformed is multiplied by a window function which is nonzero for only a short period of time.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The Fourier transform (a one-dimensional function) of the resulting signal is taken, then the window is slid along the time axis until the end resulting in a two-dimensional representation of the signal.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Often phase unwrapping is employed along either or both the time axis, $\tau$ , and frequency axis, $\omega$ , to suppress any jump discontinuity of the phase result of the STFT.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The time index $\tau$ is normally considered to be "*slow*" time and usually not expressed in as high resolution as time t .
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Given that the STFT is essentially a Fourier transform times a window function, the STFT is also called windowed Fourier transform or time-dependent Fourier transform.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] In the discrete time case, the data to be transformed could be broken up into chunks or frames (which usually overlap each other, to reduce artifacts at the boundary).
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Each chunk is Fourier transformed, and the complex result is added to a matrix, which records magnitude and phase for each point in time and frequency.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] likewise, with signal $x[n]$ and window $w[n]$ .
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] In this case, *m* is discrete and ω is continuous, but in most typical applications the STFT is performed on a computer using the fast Fourier transform, so both variables are discrete and quantized.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] See also the modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT), which is also a Fourier-related transform that uses overlapping windows.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] If only a small number of ω are desired, or if the STFT is desired to be evaluated for every shift *m* of the window, then the STFT may be more efficiently evaluated using a sliding DFT algorithm.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The STFT is invertible, that is, the original signal can be recovered from the transform by the inverse STFT.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The most widely accepted way of inverting the STFT is by using the overlap-add (OLA) method, which also allows for modifications to the STFT complex spectrum.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] This makes for a versatile signal processing method, referred to as the *overlap and add with modifications* method.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] So the Fourier transform can be seen as a sort of phase coherent sum of all of the STFTs of *x*(*t*).
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] the inverse Fourier transform of *X*(τ,ω) for τ fixed.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] One of the pitfalls of the STFT is that it has a fixed resolution.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The width of the windowing function relates to how the signal is represented—it determines whether there is good frequency resolution (frequency components close together can be separated) or good time resolution (the time at which frequencies change).
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] A wide window gives better frequency resolution but poor time resolution.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] A narrower window gives good time resolution but poor frequency resolution.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] These are called narrowband and wideband transforms, respectively.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] This is one of the reasons for the creation of the wavelet transform and multiresolution analysis, which can give good time resolution for high-frequency events and good frequency resolution for low-frequency events, the combination best suited for many real signals.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] This property is related to the Heisenberg uncertainty principle, but not directly – see Gabor limit for discussion.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The product of the standard deviation in time and frequency is limited.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The boundary of the uncertainty principle (best simultaneous resolution of both) is reached with a Gaussian window function (or mask function), as the Gaussian minimizes the Fourier uncertainty principle.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] This is called the Gabor transform (and with modifications for multiresolution becomes the Morlet wavelet transform).
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] One can consider the STFT for varying window size as a two-dimensional domain (time and frequency), as illustrated in the example below, which can be calculated by varying the window size.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] However, this is no longer a strictly time-frequency representation – the kernel is not constant over the entire signal.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Using the following sample signal $x(t)$ that is composed of a set of four sinusoidal waveforms joined together in sequence.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Each waveform is only composed of one of four frequencies (10, 25, 50, 100 Hz).
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The 25 ms window allows us to identify a precise time at which the signals change but the precise frequencies are difficult to identify.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] At the other end of the scale, the 1000 ms window allows the frequencies to be precisely seen but the time between frequency changes is blurred.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Normally we call $exp(\sigma -t^{2})$ a Gaussian function or Gabor function.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] When we use it, the short-time Fourier transform is called the "Gabor transform".
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] It can also be explained with reference to the sampling and Nyquist frequency.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Take a window of *N* samples from an arbitrary real-valued signal at sampling rate *f*s .
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Taking the Fourier transform produces *N* complex coefficients.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Of these coefficients only half are useful (the last *N/2* being the complex conjugate of the first *N/2* in reverse order, as this is a real valued signal).
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] These *N/2* coefficients represent the frequencies 0 to *f*s/2 (Nyquist) and two consecutive coefficients are spaced apart by *f*s/*N* Hz.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] To increase the frequency resolution of the window the frequency spacing of the coefficients needs to be reduced.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] There are only two variables, but decreasing *f*s (and keeping *N* constant) will cause the window size to increase — since there are now fewer samples per unit time.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The other alternative is to increase *N*, but this again causes the window size to increase.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] So any attempt to increase the frequency resolution causes a larger window size and therefore a reduction in time resolution—and vice versa.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] As the Nyquist frequency is a limitation in the maximum frequency that can be meaningfully analysed, so is the Rayleigh frequency a limitation on the minimum frequency.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The Rayleigh frequency is the minimum frequency that can be resolved by a finite duration time window.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Given a time window that is Τ seconds long, the minimum frequency that can be resolved is 1/Τ Hz.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The Rayleigh frequency is an important consideration in applications of the short-time Fourier transform (STFT), as well as any other method of harmonic analysis on a signal of finite record-length.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] STFTs as well as standard Fourier transforms and other tools are frequently used to analyze music.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The spectrogram can, for example, show frequency on the horizontal axis, with the lowest frequencies at left, and the highest at the right.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The height of each bar (augmented by color) represents the amplitude of the frequencies within that band.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] The depth dimension represents time, where each new bar was a separate distinct transform.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] Audio engineers use this kind of visual to gain information about an audio sample, for example, to locate the frequencies of specific noises (especially when used with greater frequency resolution) or to find frequencies which may be more or less resonant in the space where the signal was recorded.
[src:pitch-shifting/short-time-fourier-transform] This information can be used for equalization or tuning other audio effects.
